Welcome to the start of a new school year! We realize this has been, and continues to be, a deeply unsettling time for communities across our country. Though many things are still uncertain, please rest assured that students‚Äô education at K12-powered schools is not one of them.

In the midst of seeing unprecedented interest in our programs, our teams have been hard at work strengthening operations to better serve each student‚Äôs learning needs. Please know that any initial challenges students may face will be resolved in the coming days and weeks.

Please refer to communication from your school regarding important instructions during the high volume start to this school year, and please continue to check the K12 Help Page for updates: https://www.help.k12.com/s/article/Service-Disruption.

We are excited about the great things to come throughout this new school year, as we continue to serve our growing school community!

Destinations students have the opportunity to take exploration courses that allow them to learn more about the career pathways offered.

Get ready to bust a move!
K12 is hosting its first VIRTUAL PROM, and you're invited! While Prom 2020 may be canceled in theory, we know that the show must go on.
Any student can participate by uploading photos and videos of their dresses, tuxes, best dance moves, and more on their personal Instagram or TikTok accounts using #K12Prom and tagging @K12Learn.
Parents can join in, too, by showing how to bust a move or giving a classic chaperone headshake. To be featured in the virtual prom, all submissions must be received by May 14, 2020.
We‚Äôll feature a K12 Prom Video for all to see on Friday, May 15th at 8:00 PM (ET).
So what are you waiting for? It‚Äôs time to start planning what you‚Äôre going to wear!

post_text: Let's be honest. Schooling at home is hard. It is an investment of time, energy, and patience. I enrolled my youngest three daughters 17 years ago. Not a typo--17 years ago! I remember there were tears on some days--mostly from me! But I can now look back and know that I gave it all I had. My daughters are well educated. Each went on to college with full scholarships. Two have graduated with honors, and the youngest--pictured here--is currently applying to medical schools. I do not regret a single minute they stayed home with me. This photo was taken 17 years ago. I treasured moments when she would sleep! (You know what I mean.) Hang in there. You can do this. It is worth it. I am thinking about you today. Heidi H

Children express and receive love in different ways - some through acts of service, others through affirming words, and still others through gifts, quality time, or physical touch. Each of these expressions of love represents a different "language." Based on the book The Five Love Languages by Gary Chapman, Dr. Boyd will explain and discuss each of the love languages and provide strategies that enable parents to speak to their children's love language.

Join us this Wednesday (10/30) at 8:00pm EST to learn more on this important topic! Check out the Announcements section in OLS for details and to register.
